  section
    .container
      .row
        .col-12.my-md-5.my-3
          .row
            .col-12.col-md-8.order-first.order-md-2
              h4 #[span.fw-lighter MultispeQ]#[br]Python Libraries
            .col-12.col-md-4.order-2.order-md-first
              a.link-darken.d-block.position-relative(href="https://openjii.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") !{filters.image( filters.url("/images/jii/openJII-logo-vertical-yellow.svg"), "Data Viewer" )}
            .col-12.col-md-8.offset-md-4.order-last
              p The MultispeQ device uses a serial connection for communication with other devices using a USB cable or via Bluetooth®.
                | The first Python library allows to use scripts to control the MultispeQ and create complex measurements and experiments.
                | The second one is a collection of measurement protocols with numerous supporting functions around creating and using protocols.
              
              p The development of the libraries also includes the documentation on how to work and develop them. It is implemented using 
                | #[a(href="https://www.sphinx-doc.org/en/master/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") Sphinx] in combination with a GitHub workflow 
                | to update the documentation automatically when updates are pushed.

              p.small
                em Currently both libraries are not on yet added to The Python Package Index (PyPI) #[a(href="https://pypi.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") pypi.org] but can be installed from the Github repo.

              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="https://github.com/Jan-IngenHousz-Institute/JII-MultispeQ/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-github] JII-MultispeQ on Github
              | 
              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="https://github.com/Jan-IngenHousz-Institute/JII-MultispeQ-Protocols/", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-github] JII-MultispeQ-Protocols on Github

  section
    .container
      .row
        .col-12.my-md-5.my-3
          .row
            .col-12.col-md-8.order-first.order-md-2
              h4 #[span.fw-lighter Data Analysis]#[br]React Data Viewer
            .col-12.col-md-4.order-2.order-md-first
              a.link-darken.d-block.position-relative(href="/react-data-viewer/") !{filters.image( filters.url("/images/programming/react-data-viewer.svg"), "Data Viewer" )}
            .col-12.col-md-8.offset-md-4.order-last
              p This data viewer web application lets you bring in data from text, CSV, JSON and parquet files for analysis. You can filter data, 
                | set thresholds, define data types, and plot data. You can also perform statistical tests and add data to maps 
                | when you have geocoordinates. 
                | The analysis can be saved, including the original data, and shared with others for collaboration. 
                | Results can be added to a dashboard, which updates automatically when you filter, set thresholds, or change the selection of subsets.
                | In addition to graphs and maps, several statistical tests, notes, and <em>k</em>-means clustering are available.
              p.small
                em This is still an early version, so if you spot any issues or need any help, please let me know!
              p.small Why is React in the title? Well, the application is based on the free and open-source front-end JavaScript library #[a(href="https://react.dev" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") React], but  
               | there are many other amazing open libraries like #[a(href="https://plotly.com/", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") Plotly] for visualizing the data making this app possible.

              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="/react-data-viewer/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-binoculars] Explore Your Data
              | 
              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="https://github.com/SeBassTian23/react-data-viewer", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-github] Source on GitHub

  section
    .container
      .row
        .col-12.my-md-5.my-3
          .row
            .col-12.col-md-8.order-first.order-md-2
              h4 #[span.fw-lighter Photosynthesis]#[br]Scheme Creator
            .col-12.col-md-4.order-2.order-md-first
              a.link-darken.d-block.position-relative(href="/photosynthesis-scheme/") !{filters.image( filters.url("/images/science/photosynthesis-scheme.svg"), "Photosynthesis Scheme" )}
            .col-12.col-md-8.offset-md-4.order-last
              p Creating or modifying the Photosynthetic Scheme for presentations or posters can become time-consuming, 
                | including finding figures or previously used files, modifying, labeling, or changing colors.
                | The creator was built to easily add or remove complexes, different pathways, etc.,
                | and export the figure as a vector graphic or a regular image file.
                | It also provides a simple figure legend based on the selected elements.
              p.small The figure style is based on Kramer, D. M., Avenson, T. J. and Edwards, G. E. (2004) Dynamic flexibility in the light reactions of photosynthesis governed 
                | by both electron and proton transfer reactions. Trends Plant Sci 9, 349-357

              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="/photosynthesis-scheme", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-pencil-square] Create a Figure
              | 
              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="https://github.com/SeBassTian23/photosynthesis-scheme", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-github] Source on GitHub

  section
    .container
      .row
        .col-12.my-md-5.my-3
          .row
            .col-12.col-md-8.order-first.order-md-2
              h4 #[span.fw-lighter Data Visualization]#[br]Calendar Heatmap
            .col-12.col-md-4.order-2.order-md-first
              a.link-darken.d-block.position-relative(href="/calendar-heatmap/") !{filters.image( filters.url("/images/programming/calendar-heatmap-sm.svg"), "Calendar Heatmap" )}
            .col-12.col-md-8.offset-md-4.order-last
              p When working with time-resolved data, Calendar heatmaps can be a great tool to visualize clusters, outliers,
                | trends, and seasonal cycles over different periods, using a calendar layout with color gradients.
                | This tool makes it easy to create a heatmap from a dataset formatted as a CSV or JSON file.
                | The resulting map can be edited and saved as SVG or PNG.

              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="/calendar-heatmap", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-pencil-square] Create SVG Heatmap
              | 
              a.btn.btn-sm.btn-outline-secondary(href="https://github.com/SeBassTian23/calendar-heatmap", target="_blank" rel="noreferrer") #[i.bi.bi-github] Source on GitHub

